Node Placement in Kubernetes

What is a Node?
A node is a worker machine in your Kubernetes cluster. It can be a virtual machine or a physical server. Every node runs pods, and each pod contains containers.

What is Node Placement?
When you deploy a pod, Kubernetes must choose which node to run that pod on. This decision is called node placement.

Real world example: You order food online. The system decides which restaurant branch will prepare and deliver your food. That branch is like a node.

How Kubernetes Decides Placement by Default
Kubernetes uses a component called the scheduler. It does three things:

Looks at all available nodes
Checks their health, available CPU, memory, and other resources
Places your pod on the best suited node

Things That Affect Node Placement

1. Node Selectors
This is the simplest way to control placement. You tell Kubernetes: Only place my pod on nodes with specific labels.
Example: This pod will run only on nodes that have the label disktype=ssd.
Real benefit: Useful when some nodes have special hardware like SSDs or GPUs.

2. Node Affinity and Anti-Affinity
This is more advanced than node selectors.

Type	            Meaning
Node Affinity	    Prefer or require certain node types
Node Anti-Affinity	Avoid certain node types
Example: Require that the pod runs on a node in the us-east-1a zone.

Real benefit: You can express complex rules like "prefer nodes in zone A but also allow zone B if A is full."

3. Taints and Tolerations
Taints are applied to nodes. Tolerations are applied to pods.
Tainted node repels pods that do not have a matching toleration
Pods with the toleration can run on that node

Example: A node can be tainted to only allow system critical pods. Your pod needs a toleration to run on it.
Real benefit: Reserved nodes for specific workloads. For example, a node only for database pods.

4. Pod Affinity and Anti-Affinity
These rules are about pod to pod relationships.

Type	            Meaning
Pod Affinity	    Run this pod near another pod
Pod Anti-Affinity	Do not run this pod near that other pod

Use cases:

High availability: Run pods on different nodes so a single node failure does not bring down the service
Performance: Run pods close to each other to reduce network latency
Real benefit: Control pod placement based on where other pods are running.

5. Resource Requests and Limits
Kubernetes only places a pod on a node with enough free resources.
Example: If a pod requests 1 CPU and 1 GB of memory, it will not be scheduled on a node with less than 1 CPU and 1 GB free.
Real benefit: Prevents one pod from starving other pods. Ensures pods get the resources they need.

Summary Table
Feature	            Purpose
Node Selector	    Run on specific labeled nodes
Node Affinity	    Prefer or require certain nodes
Node Anti-Affinity	Avoid certain nodes
Taints	            Repel pods without matching toleration
Tolerations	        Allow pods to run on tainted nodes
Pod Affinity	    Run near other specific pods
Pod Anti-Affinity	Run away from specific pods
Resource Requests	Minimum resources needed
Resource Limits	    Maximum resources allowed

The Big Picture
Default scheduler behavior: Best effort based on available resources.

With placement controls: You can enforce exactly where pods should or should not run.

Control Type	        When to Use
Node Selector	        Simple hardware requirements
Node Affinity	        Complex node preferences
Taints and Tolerations	Dedicated nodes for specific teams or workloads
Pod Affinity	        Performance, low latency
Pod Anti-Affinity	    High availability, fault tolerance
Resource Requests	    Guarantee minimum resources